    "Second, the remaining red stimuli will be searched for the target shape.",
    "Because it is now a shape singleton amongst the remaining red stimuli and therefore pops out, the target will be found quickly, which is in accord with the obtained results.",
    "This account was later adapted into the feature inhibition hypothesis proposed by Treisman and Sato (1990), which was revised to suggest that multiple feature dimensions could be suppressed in parallel.",
    "This is just one of many examples of an attentional theory involving suppression (e.g., Klein, 2000; Logan et al., 2015).",
    "More recently, it has been suggested that attentional suppression plays a crucial role in the ability to ignore salient distractors (→ Features; → Stimuli)."
